  "statement": {
    "ambiguity_status": "clear",
    "intended": "A positive odd integer $m$ such that none of $2^km+1$ are prime for $k\\geq 0$ is called a Sierpinski number. We say that a set of primes $P$ is a covering set for $m$ if every $2^km+1$ is divisible by some $p\\in P$.\n\nAre there Sierpinski numbers with no finite covering set of primes?",
